                    ['| DETERMINANTS OF EXCHANGE RATE |', '', '', '', '', ''],
                    ['46', 'Interest Rate Differential', '—', 'Difference in interest rates between two countries — higher domestic interest rates attract foreign capital, appreciating the currency', 'If r_India > r_USA → Capital flows to India → Supply of USD ↑ → Rupee appreciates', 'Short-run exchange rate determinant — connects monetary policy (Chapter 3) to exchange rate — RBI raising repo rate → rupee strengthens'],
                    ['47', 'Purchasing Power Parity Theory', 'PPP', 'Long-run theory that exchange rates adjust so that the same goods cost the same in different countries after currency conversion', 'PPP Exchange Rate = Price Level_domestic / Price Level_foreign\nΔe = Difference in inflation rates', 'Long-run exchange rate theory — if India\'s inflation > USA\'s inflation → rupee depreciates over time → corrects the price level difference → trade balance restores'],
                    ['48', 'Speculation', '—', 'Buying foreign currency expecting it to appreciate — expectation alone can change the exchange rate, making beliefs self-fulfilling', 'No formula — expectation-driven mechanism', 'Short-run exchange rate determinant — can cause volatility disconnected from fundamentals — RBI intervenes under managed float to prevent speculative overshooting'],
                    ['49', 'Income Effect on Exchange Rate', '—', 'When domestic income rises, imports rise, increasing demand for foreign exchange, which tends to depreciate the domestic currency', 'ΔY_India↑ → ΔM↑ → Demand for forex ↑ → Rupee depreciates', 'Short-run determinant — connects income determination (Chapter 4) to forex market — India\'s rapid growth causes import surge → rupee depreciation pressure'],
                    // OPEN ECONOMY INCOME
                    ['| OPEN ECONOMY INCOME DETERMINATION |', '', '', '', '', ''],
                    ['50', 'Domestic Demand for Goods', '—', 'Total demand by residents of a country including demand for both domestic and foreign (imported) goods', 'Domestic Demand = C + I + G', 'Broader than demand for domestic goods — includes imports — different from AD for domestic goods (which excludes imports but includes exports)'],
                    ['51', 'Demand for Domestic Goods', '—', 'Demand for goods produced within the country — by both domestic residents AND foreigners (exports)', 'Demand for Domestic Goods = C + I + G + X − M = C + I + G + NX', 'This is what actually generates domestic income and employment — higher exports raise this; higher imports lower this'],
                    ['52', 'Import Function', '—', 'Mathematical relationship showing how total imports change with changes in national income', 'M = M̄ + mY\nM̄ = autonomous imports (imports at Y=0)\nm = MPM (Marginal Propensity to Import)', 'Imports rise with income → additional leakage from circular flow → reduces domestic multiplier — more open economy → higher m → smaller multiplier'],
                    ['53', 'Autonomous Imports', 'M̄', 'Base level of imports that occur regardless of income level — minimum essential imports like certain raw materials', 'M̄ = value of M when Y = 0\nPart of import function M = M̄ + mY', 'Part of autonomous expenditure — increase in M̄ decreases equilibrium income: ΔY/ΔM̄ = −1/(1−c+m)'],
                    ['54', 'Marginal Propensity to Import', 'MPM / m', 'The fraction of each additional rupee of income that is spent on imported goods and services', 'MPM = ΔM / ΔY = m\n0 < m < 1', 'Key parameter reducing open economy multiplier — higher m → smaller multiplier → more of each income round leaks to foreign producers → smaller domestic income effect'],
                    ['55', 'Open Economy Equilibrium Income', 'Y*', 'Level of national income where aggregate demand equals aggregate supply including exports and imports', 'Y* = A / (1 − c + m)\nwhere A = all autonomous expenditure including X̄ − M̄', 'Lower than closed economy equilibrium for same autonomous expenditure (because multiplier is smaller) — changes when X, M̄, G, C̄, or I change'],
                    ['56', 'Open Economy Multiplier', '—', 'Ratio of change in equilibrium income to change in autonomous expenditure in an open economy — smaller than closed economy multiplier', 'Open Economy Multiplier = 1 / (1 − c + m) = 1 / (MPS + MPM)', 'Always smaller than closed economy multiplier (1/MPS) because imports are additional leakage — the more open the economy (higher m), the smaller the multiplier'],
                    ['57', 'Export Multiplier', '—', 'The ratio showing how much equilibrium income changes when exports change', 'ΔY/ΔX = 1 / (1 − c + m) = Open Economy Multiplier', 'Same size as open economy autonomous expenditure multiplier — export increase is an injection → income rises by open multiplier times ΔX'],
                    ['58', 'Import Leakage', '—', 'The fraction of each income round that leaks out of the domestic economy as spending on foreign goods — reduces the multiplier', 'Import Leakage per round = m × ΔY at each multiplier stage', 'Additional leakage alongside saving (MPS) — total leakage per round = MPS + MPM → denominator of open economy multiplier = 1−c+m'],
                    ['59', 'Trade Balance Effect', '—', 'Impact of changes in autonomous expenditure on the net export (trade) balance in open economy', 'ΔNX for ΔG = −m × ΔY = −m/(1−c+m) × ΔG', 'When government spending rises → income rises → imports rise → trade balance WORSENS even as income improves — policy tradeoff'],
                    // ADDITIONAL CONCEPTS
                    ['| ADDITIONAL CONCEPTS |', '', '', '', '', ''],
                    ['60', 'Current Account Deficit', 'CAD', 'Situation where a country spends more on imports of goods, services and transfers than it earns from exports and inflows', 'CAD = Current Account Payments − Current Account Receipts\nCAD > 0 means deficit', 'Must be financed by Capital Account surplus — persistent CAD may weaken domestic currency (under flexible rates) or deplete forex reserves (under fixed rates)'],
                    ['61', 'Financial Account', '—', 'In the new IMF BPM6 classification, the account that records all financial asset transactions — trade in bonds, equity, FDI etc.', 'Under BPM6: BoP = Current Account + Capital Account (new) + Financial Account', 'New classification by IMF — RBI still publishes using old system too — Financial Account captures what old Capital Account mostly covered for financial investments'],
                    ['62', 'Tariff', '—', 'Tax imposed on imported goods — raises the domestic price of imports — used to protect domestic industry or raise revenue', 'No formula — policy tool; affects: imports, BoT, exchange rate, PPP', 'Barrier to trade — PPP theory works when NO tariffs or quotas exist — tariffs reduce trade openness → reduce import leakage → modify open economy multiplier'],
                    ['63', 'Quota', '—', 'Quantitative limit on the amount of specific goods that can be imported — a non-tariff barrier to trade', 'No formula — policy measure; Example: Import only 1000 tonnes of sugar', 'Restricts trade unlike exchange rate depreciation — PPP theory assumes no quotas — limits quantity of imports regardless of price'],
                    ['64', 'Hot Money', '—', 'Short-term foreign capital (mainly FPI/FII) that moves quickly across borders seeking highest returns — highly volatile', 'No formula — describes volatile short-term capital flows', 'Destabilising for exchange rate and BoP — sudden outflows cause currency crisis — RBI limits some types of hot money inflows — FDI is more stable than FPI'],
                    ['65', 'Commercial Borrowings', 'ECB', 'Accumulation or repayment of international debt impacting fundamental liabilities', 'Impacts Capital Account, Debit side for outflows', '"Net outflow of commercial borrowings" reflects more repayment made than new borrowing taken, aggressively reducing forex reserves (−).'],
                    ['66', 'BoP Deficit (Technical)', '—', 'Strictly occurs when autonomous receipts fall structurally short of autonomous payments during a given fiscal year in an economy.', 'Autonomous Receipts < Autonomous Payments', 'Forces a net drain on the nation\'s official reserves (ORT) to essentially cover the persistent shortfall.'],
                    ['67', 'Trade Deficit vs CAD', '—', 'A Trade Deficit (Imports of Goods > Exports of Goods) does NOT strictly guarantee a Current Account Deficit (CAD).', 'CAD = Trade Deficit + Net Invisibles', 'A massive Trade Deficit can be robustly and completely offset by a massive surplus in Invisibles (Services/Transfers) leaving the overall Current Account firmly in surplus.']
